goals.question: What is the overall trend of unemployment rate?

goals.rationale: This helps to identify if the unemployment rate is increasing, decreasing or remaining constant over time.

goals.rationale: This helps to identify if there are any significant differences in unemployment rate across different regions.

goals.question: What is the correlation between unemployment rate and GDP?
goals.visualization: scatter plot of rate and GDP
goals.rationale: This helps to identify if there is any relationship between unemployment rate and GDP.

goals.question: What is the average unemployment rate?
goals.rationale: This helps to identify the overall average unemployment rate.

goals.question: What is the unemployment rate for the top 10 regions with the highest GDP?
goals.visualization: bar chart of rate for top 10 regions by GDP
goals.rationale: This helps to identify if there is any correlation between GDP and unemployment rate for the top 10 regions with the highest GDP.

import seaborn as sns
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    data['date'] = pd.to_datetime(data['id'], format='%Y%m', errors='coerce')
    sns.lineplot(x='date', y='rate', data=data)
    plt.title('What is the overall trend of unemployment rate?', wrap=True)
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)

import seaborn as sns
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    data['id'] = data['id'].astype(str)
    sns.boxplot(x='id', y='rate', data=data)
    plt.title('What is the distribution of unemployment rate across different regions?', wrap=True)
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)

import seaborn as sns
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    data['rate'] = pd.to_numeric(data['rate'], errors='coerce')
    data['GDP'] = pd.to_numeric(data['GDP'], errors='coerce')
    sns.scatterplot(x='GDP', y='rate', data=data)
    plt.title('What is the correlation between unemployment rate and GDP?', wrap=True)
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)

import seaborn as sns
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    data['rate'] = pd.to_numeric(data['rate'], errors='coerce')
    avg_rate = data['rate'].mean()
    ax = sns.barplot(x=['Average Rate'], y=[avg_rate], palette='Blues')
    ax.axhline(avg_rate, color='red', label=f'Average Rate: {avg_rate:.2f}')
    ax.legend()
    plt.title('What is the average unemployment rate?', wrap=True)
    return plt

chart = plot(data)

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    data = data.sort_values(by='GDP', ascending=False).head(10)
    sns.barplot(x='id', y='rate', data=data)
    plt.title('What is the unemployment rate for the top 10 regions with the highest GDP?', wrap=True)
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)
